value.value: A papillary tumor originating in the renal pelvis.
A neoplasm (disease) that involves the renal pelvis.
A usually aggressive malignant neoplasm arising from the kidney. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped fibroblasts and collagenous stroma formation in a herringbone growth pattern.
An osteosarcoma arising from the kidney.
A meningioma that affects the internal auditory canal.
Breast adenosis characterized by the presence of ducts with distended lumen and columnar cell metaplasia.

label.value: non-proliferative fibrocystic change of the breast

value.value: Breast fibrocystic change characterized by the absence of epithelial cell hyperplasia.
A non-neoplastic disorder characterized by epithelial and/or myoepithelial tissue growth in the breast lobules. It may be associated with apocrine changes or sclerosis.
Breast adenosis characterized by the presence of extensive apocrine metaplasia.
An overwhelming, irrational, and persistent fear of animals.
A usually aggressive malignant neoplasm arising from the breast. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped fibroblasts and collagenous stroma formation in a herringbone growth pattern.

Infiltration of the skin and subcutaneous tissue by leukemic cells without evidence of leukemia in the bone marrow and peripheral blood. It results in clinically identifiable skin lesions. It may be the first manifestation of acute leukemia, preceding the involvement of the bone marrow and peripheral blood by the leukemic process.
A leukemia characterized by the absence of leukemic cells in the peripheral blood.
A mature or immature teratoma affecting the central nervous system and occurring in adults.

label.value: adult central nervous system mature teratoma

value.value: A central nervous system mature teratoma that occurs in an adult.

A teratoma composed exclusively of fully differentiated, 'adult-type' tissue elements that are sometimes arranged in a pattern resembling normal tissue relationships. Mitotic activity is low or absent. The more common ectodermal components present in a mature teratoma include skin, brain and choroid plexus. The more common mesodermal components include cartilage, bone, fat and muscle (both smooth and striated). And the most common endodermal components are cysts lined by epithelia of respiratory or enteric type and in some cases pancreatic or hepatic tissue. (Adapted from WHO)

label.value: adult central nervous system immature teratoma

value.value: A variant of teratoma composed of incompletely differentiated components resembling fetal tissues. Even if the immature component is only a minor element of an otherwise differentiated teratoma, the tumor is still classified as immature. (Adapted from WHO)
An overwhelming, irrational, and persistent fear of being diagnosed with cancer.
A Leydig cell tumor characterized by a large size, cellular atypia, high mitotic activity, vascular invasion and necrotic changes. The prognosis is usually poor.

A rare dysgammaglobulinemia characterized by low or undetectable serum levels of immunoglobulin class E (IgE). It is an uncommon primary antibody deficiency. It is most likely an inherited immunodeficiency. It may be caused by decreased or inefficient class-switching from progenitor B cells without any corresponding decreases in the other isotypes. Most affected persons appear asymptomatic but may show a predisposition to autoimmune and respiratory diseases.

A broad classification of dysgammaglobulinemias characterized by low or undetectable serum levels of one of the five immunoglobulin classes. Deficiencies of immunoglobulins present variably according to isotype. Selective deficiencies may be caused by decreased or inefficient production from progenitor B cells without any corresponding decreases in the other isotypes. The clinical course and prognosis is dependent upon the severity of the selective deficiency and associated morbidity.
An overwhelming, irrational, and persistent fear of contracting Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome.

label.value: juvenile type testicular granulosa cell tumor

value.value: A rare sex cord-stromal tumor that arises from the testis. It is the most frequent congenital testicular neoplasm and is usually diagnosed during the perinatal period. It usually presents as an asymptomatic scrotal or abdominal mass. Morphologically it is characterized by the presence of cysts that are lined by cells resembling granulosa and theca cells.
A usually aggressive malignant neoplasm arising from the heart. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped fibroblasts and collagenous stroma formation in a herringbone growth pattern.
A malignant hemangiopericytoma arising in the heart.

value.value: A melanoma arising from the choroid, ciliary body, or the iris. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped melanocytes.
A spindle cell melanoma that involves the optic choroid.
A spindle cell melanoma that involves the ciliary body.
A glomus tumor characterized by huge vascular channel formations.
An overwhelming, irrational, and persistent fear of traveling in an aircraft.

A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the esophagus. Representative examples of non-neoplastic disorders include esophagitis and esophageal ulcer. Representative examples of neoplastic disorders include carcinomas, lymphomas, and melanomas.

label.value: childhood central nervous system germ cell tumor

value.value: A germ cell tumor of the central nervous system occurring in children.
A germ cell tumor that occurs during childhood.
A papilloma that arises from the ciliated respiratory mucosa that lines the frontal sinus. It is classified as inverted papilloma and oncocytic papilloma.
A benign exophytic squamous cell neoplasm with papillary growth that arises from the nasal vestibule.

Brown-Sequard syndrome is a rare neurological condition that results from an injury or damage to one side of the spinal cord. This condition results in weakness or paralysis on one side of the body (hemiparaplegia) and a loss of sensation on the opposite side (hemianesthesia). Brown-Sequard syndrome most commonly occurs in the the thoracic spine (upper and middle back). There are several causes of Brown-Sequard syndrome, including: a spinal cord tumor, trauma (such as a puncture wound to the neck or back), infectious or inflammatory diseases (tuberculosis or multiple sclerosis), and disk herniation. Treatment for this condition varies depending on the underlying cause.

label.value: urinary tract non-invasive transitional cell neoplasm

value.value: A benign, borderline, or malignant epithelial tumor of the ovary characterized by the presence of neoplastic epithelial cells that contain intracytoplasmic mucin and may resemble the epithelial cells of the endocervix or gastrointestinal tract.
Complete paralysis of the lower half of the body including both legs, often caused by damage to the spinal cord.
A germ cell tumor that arises from the testis during childhood.
A yolk sac tumor that arises from the ovary and occurs in children.
A germ cell tumor that arises from the ovary and occurs in children.
A melanoma that arises from leptomeningeal melanocytes.

value.value: A primary or metastatic malignant tumor involving the leptomeninges.

An anxiety disorder precipitated by an experience of intense fear or horror while exposed to a traumatic (especially life-threatening) event. The disorder is characterized by dissociative symptoms; vivid recollections of the traumatic event; avoidance of stimuli associated with the traumatic event; and a constant state of hyperarousal for no more than one month.
A melanoma that arises from leptomeningeal melanocytes and occurs in childhood.
A melanoma that arises from leptomeningeal melanocytes and occurs in adulthood.
A cancer involving a dorsal plus ventral thalamus.
